


'''Megan Boyle''' (born 1985) is an American writer and filmmaker.

Boyle grew up in Baltimore, and rose to prominence among the [[Alt lit|Alt Lit]] and internet community after writing popular articles for Thought Catalog<ref>{{cite web|last=Philips |first=Dylan |url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/megan-boyle/2010/10/everyone-sex-list-people-humans/ |title=Everyone I've Had Sex With |publisher=Thought Catalog |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref> and marrying writer [[Tao Lin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Philips |first=Dylan |url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/brandon-gorrell/2011/01/tao-lin-and-megan-boyle-of-mdma-films-are-married/ |title=Tao Lin and Megan Boyle Get Married |publisher=Thought Catalog |date=2011-01-08 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>
Together, Boyle and Lin created several movies for their company MDMA films, which they began in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/tao_lin_and_megan_boyle_talk_mdma_films |title=INTERVIEW &#124; Drugs, Meet Movies: Tao Lin and Megan Boyle's MDMAfilms &#124; Filmmakers, Film Industry, Film Festivals, Awards & Movie Reviews |publisher=Indiewire |date= |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>. In 2011, Lin published Boyle's poetry collection, ''selected unpublished blog posts of a mexican panda express employee'', which garnered favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hales |first=Dianne R. |url=http://bnreview.barnesandnoble.com/t5/Discover-Great-New-Writers/What-to-Read-Kevin-Wilson-Recommends/ba-p/7715 |title=What to Read? Kevin Wilson Recommends - The Barnes & Noble Review |publisher=Bnreview.barnesandnoble.com |date=2012-05-02 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://malloryrice.tumblr.com/post/12332742776/this-is-the-last-shelf-help-of-the-year-were |title=Mallory 8. Rice |publisher=Malloryrice.tumblr.com |date=2011-11-04 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2012/03/selected-unpublished-blog-posts-of-a-mexican-panda-express-employee/ |title=Selected Unpublished Blog Posts Of A Mexican Panda Express Employee |publisher=The Rumpus.net |date=2012-03-10 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>
From 2011-2013, Boyle wrote a column for [[Vice magazine|Vice Magazine]] called Boyle's Brains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vice.com/columns/Boyles-Brains |title=The Definitive Guide To Enlightening Information &#124; VICE Today &#124; United States |publisher=Vice.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>
On March 17, 2013<ref>{{cite web|author=Name * |url=http://altcitizen.com/2013/08/05/keeping-it-real-or-whatever-with-megan-boyle/ |title=Keeping It Real<U+2013>Or Whatever<U+2013>with Megan Boyle &#124; Alt Citizen Magazine |publisher=Altcitizen.com |date=2013-08-05 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>, she began "liveblogging," or documenting her daily activities through her Tumblr, which critics praised as a "painfully honest and raw record of a person<U+2019>s life"<ref name="electricliterature">{{cite web|last=Escoria |first=Juliet |url=http://electricliterature.com/blog/2013/08/28/interview-liveblogging-with-megan-boyle/ |title=Interview: Liveblogging with Megan Boyle &#124; The Outlet: the Blog of Electric Literature |publisher=Electricliterature.com |date=2013-08-28 |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>. She ceased the project in September; by then it was over 350,000 words long <ref name="electricliterature" />

Boyle has been profiled by magazines such as Nylon and Elle<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com/news/culture/writer-megan-boyle-calls-her-style-coyly-asexual-32250 |title=Writer Megan Boyle Calls Her Style 'Coyly Asexual' |publisher=ELLE |date= |accessdate=2014-01-21}}</ref>. Her work has been published in places such as 3:AM Magazine, Pear Noir!, and Pop Serial. She currently lives in New York.

